<section><title>user shell</title>
	<section><title>login shell</title>
		<para>The <command>/etc/passwd</command> file determines the login shell for the user. In the screenshot below you can see that user annelies receives the /bin/bash shell, and user laura receives the /bin/ksh shell when they login.</para>
		<screen>
[root@RHEL5 ~]# tail -2 /etc/passwd
annelies:x:527:533:sword fighter:/home/annelies:/bin/bash
laura:x:528:534:art dealer:/home/laura:/bin/ksh
		</screen>
		<para>You can use the usermod command to change the shell for a user.</para>
		<screen>
[root@RHEL5 ~]# usermod -s /bin/bash laura
[root@RHEL5 ~]# tail -1 /etc/passwd
laura:x:528:534:art dealer:/home/laura:/bin/bash
		</screen>
	</section>
	<section><title>chsh</title>
		<para>Users can change their own login shell with the <command>chsh</command><indexterm><primary>chsh(1)</primary></indexterm> command. User harry here is first obtaining a list of available shells ( the user could have done a cat <command>/etc/shells</command><indexterm><primary>/etc/shells</primary></indexterm> ) and then changes his login shell to the <command>Korn shell</command><indexterm><primary>Korn Shell</primary></indexterm> (/bin/ksh). At the next login, harry will default into ksh instead of bash. </para>
		<screen>
[harry@RHEL4 ~]$ chsh -l
/bin/sh
/bin/bash
/sbin/nologin
/bin/ash
/bin/bsh
/bin/ksh
/usr/bin/ksh
/usr/bin/pdksh
/bin/tcsh
/bin/csh
/bin/zsh
[harry@RHEL4 ~]$ chsh -s /bin/ksh
Changing shell for harry.
Password: 
Shell changed.
[harry@RHEL4 ~]$
		</screen>
	</section>
</section>
